msgctxt "dn3:1.1"
msgid "Dīgha Nikāya 3"
msgstr "Long Discourses 3"

#. </p><h1>
msgctxt "dn3:2.1"
msgid "Ambaṭṭhasutta"
msgstr "With Ambaṭṭha"

#. </h1></div><p><a class="sc" id="1"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.1"></a><a
#. class="pts" id="pts1.87"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:3.1"
msgid "<span class=\"evam\">Evaṃ me sutaṃ—​</span>"
msgstr "<span class=”evam”>So have I heard.</span>"

msgctxt "dn3:3.2"
msgid ""
"ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā kosalesu cārikaṃ caramāno mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena "
"saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi yena icchānaṅgalaṃ nāma kosalānaṃ "
"brāhmaṇagāmo tadavasari."
msgstr ""
"At one time the Buddha was wandering in the land of the Kosalans together "
"with a large Saṅgha of around five hundred mendicants when he arrived at a "
"village of the Kosalan brahmins called Icchānaṅgala."

msgctxt "dn3:3.3"
msgid "Tatra sudaṃ bhagavā icchānaṅgale viharati icchānaṅgalavanasaṇḍe."
msgstr "He stayed on in a forest near Icchānaṅgala."

#. </p><h2>
msgctxt "dn3:4.1"
msgid "1. Pokkharasātivatthu"
msgstr "The Section on Pokkharasāti"

#. </h2><p><a class="sc" id="2"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.2"></a><a class="pts"
#. id="pts1.88"></a>
#. VAR: pokkharasāti → pokkharasātī (bj) | pokkharasādi (pts1)
msgctxt "dn3:5.1"
msgid ""
"Tena kho pana samayena brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti ukkaṭṭhaṃ ajjhāvasati "
"sattussadaṃ satiṇakaṭṭhodakaṃ sadhaññaṃ rājabhoggaṃ raññā pasenadinā "
"kosalena dinnaṃ rājadāyaṃ brahmadeyyaṃ."
msgstr ""
"Now at that time the brahmin Pokkharasāti was living in Ukkaṭṭhā. It was a "
"crown property given by King Pasenadi of Kosala, teeming with living "
"creatures, full of hay, wood, water, and grain, a royal endowment of the "
"highest quality."

msgctxt "dn3:5.2"
msgid "Assosi kho brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti:"
msgstr "Pokkharasāti heard:"

msgctxt "dn3:5.3"
msgid ""
"“samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo sakyaputto sakyakulā pabbajito kosalesu cārikaṃ "
"caramāno mahatā bhikkhusaṃghena saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi "
"icchānaṅgalaṃ anuppatto icchānaṅgale viharati icchānaṅgalavanasaṇḍe."
msgstr ""
"“It seems the ascetic Gotama—a Sakyan, gone forth from a Sakyan family—has "
"arrived at Icchānaṅgala and is staying in a forest nearby."

msgctxt "dn3:5.4"
msgid "Taṃ kho pana bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ evaṃ kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggato:"
msgstr "He has this good reputation:"

#. VAR: bhagavā → bhagavāti (s1-3, km)
msgctxt "dn3:5.5"
msgid ""
"‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū "
"anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā ’."
msgstr ""
"‘That Blessed One is perfect, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in "
"knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme trainer of people, "
"teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’"

msgctxt "dn3:5.6"
msgid ""
"So imaṃ lokaṃ sadevakaṃ samārakaṃ sabrahmakaṃ sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiṃ pajaṃ "
"sadevamanussaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti."
msgstr ""
"He has realized with his own insight this world—with its gods, Māras and "
"Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—and "
"he makes it known to others."

msgctxt "dn3:5.7"
msgid ""
"So dhammaṃ deseti ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ, sātthaṃ "
"sabyañjanaṃ, kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāseti."
msgstr ""
"He teaches Dharma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good "
"in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And he reveals a spiritual practice "
"that’s entirely full and pure."

msgctxt "dn3:5.8"
msgid "Sādhu kho pana tathārūpānaṃ arahataṃ dassanaṃ hotī”ti."
msgstr "It’s good to see such perfected ones.”"

#. </p><h2>
msgctxt "dn3:6.1"
msgid "2. Ambaṭṭhamāṇava"
msgstr "The Brahmin Student Ambaṭṭha"

# For anuññātapaṭiññāta see MN 98, for tevijjake pāvacane see MN 95
#. </h2><p><a class="sc" id="3"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.3"></a>
#. VAR: vedānaṃ → bedānaṃ (mr)
msgctxt "dn3:7.1"
msgid ""
"Tena kho pana samayena brāhmaṇassa pokkharasātissa ambaṭṭho nāma māṇavo "
"antevāsī hoti ajjhāyako mantadharo tiṇṇaṃ vedānaṃ pāragū "
"sanighaṇḍukeṭubhānaṃ sākkharappabhedānaṃ itihāsapañcamānaṃ padako "
"veyyākaraṇo lokāyatamahāpurisalakkhaṇesu anavayo anuññātapaṭiññāto sake "
"ācariyake tevijjake pāvacane:"
msgstr ""
"Now at that time Pokkharasāti had a student named Ambaṭṭha. He was one who "
"recited and remembered the hymns, and was an expert in the three Vedas, "
"together with their vocabularies, ritual, phonology and etymology, and the "
"testament as fifth. He knew philology and grammar, and was well versed in "
"cosmology and the marks of a great man. He had been authorized as a master "
"in his own teacher’s scriptural heritage of the three Vedas with the words:"

# Compare the words of Alara Kalama and Uddaka Ramaputta to the bodhisatta.
msgctxt "dn3:7.2"
msgid "“yamahaṃ jānāmi taṃ tvaṃ jānāsi;"
msgstr "“What I know, you know."

msgctxt "dn3:7.3"
msgid "yaṃ tvaṃ jānāsi tamahaṃ jānāmī”ti."
msgstr "And what you know, I know.”"

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="4"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.4"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:8.1"
msgid "Atha kho brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ āmantesi:"
msgstr "Then Pokkharasāti addressed Ambaṭṭha:"

msgctxt "dn3:8.2"
msgid ""
"“ayaṃ, tāta ambaṭṭha, samaṇo gotamo sakyaputto sakyakulā pabbajito kosalesu "
"cārikaṃ caramāno mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi "
"icchānaṅgalaṃ anuppatto icchānaṅgale viharati icchānaṅgalavanasaṇḍe."
msgstr ""
"“Dear Ambaṭṭha, the ascetic Gotama—a Sakyan, gone forth from a Sakyan family—"
"has arrived at Icchānaṅgala and is staying in a forest nearby. …"

msgctxt "dn3:8.3"
msgid "Taṃ kho pana bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ evaṃ kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggato:"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "dn3:8.4"
msgid ""
"‘itipi so bhagavā, arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū "
"anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "dn3:8.5"
msgid ""
"So imaṃ lokaṃ sadevakaṃ samārakaṃ sabrahmakaṃ sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiṃ pajaṃ "
"sadevamanussaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "dn3:8.6"
msgid ""
"So dhammaṃ deseti ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ, sātthaṃ "
"sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāseti."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "dn3:8.7"
msgid "Sādhu kho pana tathārūpānaṃ arahataṃ dassanaṃ hotī’ti."
msgstr "It’s good to see such perfected ones."

msgctxt "dn3:8.8"
msgid "Ehi tvaṃ, tāta ambaṭṭha, yena samaṇo gotamo tenupasaṅkama;"
msgstr "Please, dear Ambaṭṭha, go to the ascetic Gotama"

msgctxt "dn3:8.9"
msgid ""
"upasaṅkamitvā samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ jānāhi, yadi vā taṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ "
"tathāsantaṃyeva saddo abbhuggato, yadi vā no tathā."
msgstr "and find out whether or not he lives up to his reputation."

# See my note on MN 91 referring to BB's note on variants for this passage.
msgctxt "dn3:8.10"
msgid ""
"Yadi vā so bhavaṃ gotamo tādiso, yadi vā na tādiso, tathā mayaṃ taṃ "
"bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ vedissāmā”ti."
msgstr "Through you I shall learn about Mister Gotama.”"

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="5"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.5"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:9.1"
msgid "“Yathā kathaṃ panāhaṃ, bho, taṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ jānissāmi:"
msgstr ""
"“But how, sir, shall I find out whether or not the ascetic Gotama lives up "
"to his reputation?”"

#, fuzzy
msgctxt "dn3:9.2"
msgid ""
"‘yadi vā taṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ tathāsantaṃyeva saddo abbhuggato, yadi vā no "
"tathā."
msgstr " "

msgctxt "dn3:9.3"
msgid "Yadi vā so bhavaṃ gotamo tādiso, yadi vā na tādiso’”ti?"
msgstr ""

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="6"></a><a class="pts" id="pts1.89"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:10.1"
msgid ""
"“Āgatāni kho, tāta ambaṭṭha, amhākaṃ mantesu dvattiṃsa mahāpurisalakkhaṇāni, "
"yehi samannāgatassa mahāpurisassa dveyeva gatiyo bhavanti anaññā."
msgstr ""
"“Dear Ambaṭṭha, the thirty-two marks of a great man have been handed down in "
"our hymns. A great man who possesses these has only two possible destinies, "
"no other."

msgctxt "dn3:10.2"
msgid ""
"Sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī dhammiko dhammarājā cāturanto "
"vijitāvī janapadatthāvariyappatto sattaratanasamannāgato."
msgstr ""
"If he stays at home he becomes a king, a wheel-turning monarch, a just and "
"principled king. His dominion extends to all four sides, he achieves "
"stability in the country, and he possesses the seven treasures."

msgctxt "dn3:10.3"
msgid "Tassimāni satta ratanāni bhavanti."
msgstr "He has the following seven treasures:"

msgctxt "dn3:10.4"
msgid "Seyyathidaṃ—"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "dn3:10.5"
msgid ""
"cakkaratanaṃ, hatthiratanaṃ, assaratanaṃ, maṇiratanaṃ, itthiratanaṃ, "
"gahapatiratanaṃ, pariṇāyakaratanameva sattamaṃ."
msgstr ""
"the wheel, the elephant, the horse, the jewel, the woman, the treasurer, and "
"the counselor as the seventh treasure."

msgctxt "dn3:10.6"
msgid ""
"Parosahassaṃ kho panassa puttā bhavanti sūrā vīraṅgarūpā parasenappamaddanā."
msgstr ""
"He has over a thousand sons who are valiant and heroic, crushing the armies "
"of his enemies."

msgctxt "dn3:10.7"
msgid ""
"So imaṃ pathaviṃ sāgarapariyantaṃ adaṇḍena asatthena dhammena abhivijiya "
"ajjhāvasati."
msgstr ""
"After conquering this land girt by sea, he reigns by principle, without rod "
"or sword."

msgctxt "dn3:10.8"
msgid ""
"Sace kho pana agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati, arahaṃ hoti sammāsambuddho loke "
"vivaṭṭacchado."
msgstr ""
"But if he goes forth from the lay life to homelessness, he becomes a "
"perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha, who draws back the veil from the "
"world.”"

# The relation between Pokkarasati and his student here is strikingly similar to the relation between the Buddha and the arahants. They know the same thing, but the Buddha is distinguished as the teacher.
msgctxt "dn3:10.9"
msgid "Ahaṃ kho pana, tāta ambaṭṭha, mantānaṃ dātā;"
msgstr "But, dear Ambaṭṭha, I am the one who gives the hymns,"

msgctxt "dn3:10.10"
msgid "tvaṃ mantānaṃ paṭiggahetā”ti."
msgstr "and you are the one who receives them.”"

# While it is not always possible to clearly distinguish manava and manavaka, in this sutta the former is always applied to Ambattha, and the latter to the rest. It seems that, as a diminutive, manavaka means "young students", or perhaps more precisely, "students of a student".
#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="7"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.6"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:11.1"
msgid ""
"“Evaṃ, bho”ti kho ambaṭṭho māṇavo brāhmaṇassa pokkharasātissa paṭissutvā "
"uṭṭhāyāsanā brāhmaṇaṃ pokkharasātiṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā "
"vaḷavārathamāruyha sambahulehi māṇavakehi saddhiṃ yena icchānaṅgalavanasaṇḍo "
"tena pāyāsi."
msgstr ""
"“Yes, sir,” replied Ambaṭṭha. He got up from his seat, bowed, and "
"respectfully circled Pokkharasāti, keeping him to his right. He mounted a "
"mare-drawn chariot and, together with several students, set out for the "
"forest near Icchānaṅgala."

msgctxt "dn3:11.2"
msgid ""
"Yāvatikā yānassa bhūmi yānena gantvā yānā paccorohitvā pattikova ārāmaṃ "
"pāvisi."
msgstr ""
"He went by carriage as far as the terrain allowed, then descended and "
"entered the monastery on foot."

#. <a class="wp" id="wp1.7"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:11.3"
msgid "Tena kho pana samayena sambahulā bhikkhū abbhokāse caṅkamanti."
msgstr ""
"At that time several mendicants were walking meditation in the open air."

msgctxt "dn3:11.4"
msgid "Atha kho ambaṭṭho māṇavo yena te bhikkhū tenupasaṅkami;"
msgstr "Then the Buddha went up to those mendicants"

msgctxt "dn3:11.5"
msgid "upasaṅkamitvā te bhikkhū etadavoca:"
msgstr "and said:"

msgctxt "dn3:11.6"
msgid "“kahaṃ nu kho, bho, etarahi so bhavaṃ gotamo viharati?"
msgstr "“Gentlemen, where is Master Gotama staying now?"

# Compare the idiom in MN 35.
msgctxt "dn3:11.7"
msgid "Tañhi mayaṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya idhūpasaṅkantā”ti."
msgstr "For we have come here to see him.”"

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="8"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.8"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:12.1"
msgid "Atha kho tesaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ etadahosi:"
msgstr "Then those mendicants thought:"

msgctxt "dn3:12.2"
msgid ""
"“ayaṃ kho ambaṭṭho māṇavo abhiññātakolañño ceva abhiññātassa ca brāhmaṇassa "
"pokkharasātissa antevāsī."
msgstr ""
"“This Ambaṭṭha is from a well-known family, and he is the pupil of the well-"
"known brahmin Pokkharasāti. "

msgctxt "dn3:12.3"
msgid ""
"Agaru kho pana bhagavato evarūpehi kulaputtehi saddhiṃ kathāsallāpo hotī”ti."
msgstr ""
"The Buddha won’t mind having a discussion together with such respectable "
"persons.”"

msgctxt "dn3:12.4"
msgid "Te ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ etadavocuṃ:"
msgstr "They said to Ambaṭṭha:"

msgctxt "dn3:12.5"
msgid ""
"“eso, ambaṭṭha, vihāro saṃvutadvāro, tena appasaddo upasaṅkamitvā ataramāno "
"āḷindaṃ pavisitvā ukkāsitvā aggaḷaṃ ākoṭehi, vivarissati te bhagavā "
"dvāran”ti."
msgstr ""
"“Ambaṭṭha, that’s his dwelling, with the door closed. Approach it quietly, "
"without hurrying; go onto the porch, clear your throat, and knock with the "
"latch. The Buddha will open the door.”"

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="9"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.9"></a><a class="pts"
#. id="pts1.90"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:13.1"
msgid ""
"Atha kho ambaṭṭho māṇavo yena so vihāro saṃvutadvāro, tena appasaddo "
"upasaṅkamitvā ataramāno āḷindaṃ pavisitvā ukkāsitvā aggaḷaṃ ākoṭesi."
msgstr "So he approached the Buddha’s dwelling and knocked,"

msgctxt "dn3:13.2"
msgid "Vivari bhagavā dvāraṃ."
msgstr "and the Buddha opened the door."

msgctxt "dn3:13.3"
msgid "Pāvisi ambaṭṭho māṇavo."
msgstr ""

# A nice little detail that ullustrates the sense of the word "sambahula", which should normally be taken in the sense of "several", rather than "many". The Buddha's kuti surely could only have accommodated a few people at a time.
msgctxt "dn3:13.4"
msgid ""
"Māṇavakāpi pavisitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu, sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ "
"sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu."
msgstr ""
"Ambaṭṭha and the other students entered the dwelling and exchanged greetings "
"with the Buddha. When the greetings and polite conversation were over, they "
"sat down to one side."

#. VAR: kañci kañci → kiñci kiñci (c1)
msgctxt "dn3:13.5"
msgid ""
"Ambaṭṭho pana māṇavo caṅkamantopi nisinnena bhagavatā kañci kañci kathaṃ "
"sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāreti, ṭhitopi nisinnena bhagavatā kañci kañci kathaṃ "
"sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāreti."
msgstr ""
"But while the Buddha was sitting, Ambaṭṭha spoke some polite words or other "
"while walking around or standing."

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="10"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.10"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:14.1"
msgid "Atha kho bhagavā ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ etadavoca:"
msgstr "So the Buddha said to him:"

msgctxt "dn3:14.2"
msgid ""
"“evaṃ nu te, ambaṭṭha, brāhmaṇehi vuddhehi mahallakehi ācariyapācariyehi "
"saddhiṃ kathāsallāpo hoti, yathayidaṃ caraṃ tiṭṭhaṃ nisinnena mayā kiñci "
"kiñci kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretī”ti?"
msgstr ""
"“Ambaṭṭha, is this how you hold a discussion with elderly and senior "
"brahmins, the teachers of teachers: walking around or standing while I’m "
"sitting, speaking some polite words or other?”"

#. </p><h3>
msgctxt "dn3:15.1"
msgid "2.1. Paṭhamaibbhavāda"
msgstr "The First Use of the Word “Riffraff”"

#. </h3><p><a class="sc" id="11"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:16.1"
msgid "“No hidaṃ, bho gotama."
msgstr "“No, Master Gotama."

msgctxt "dn3:16.2"
msgid ""
"Gacchanto vā hi, bho gotama, gacchantena brāhmaṇo brāhmaṇena saddhiṃ "
"sallapitumarahati, ṭhito vā hi, bho gotama, ṭhitena brāhmaṇo brāhmaṇena "
"saddhiṃ sallapitumarahati, nisinno vā hi, bho gotama, nisinnena brāhmaṇo "
"brāhmaṇena saddhiṃ sallapitumarahati, sayāno vā hi, bho gotama, sayānena "
"brāhmaṇo brāhmaṇena saddhiṃ sallapitumarahati."
msgstr ""
"For it is proper for one brahmin to converse with another while both are "
"walking, standing, sitting, or lying down."

#. VAR: kaṇhā → kiṇhā (pts1, mr)
msgctxt "dn3:16.3"
msgid ""
"Ye ca kho te, bho gotama, muṇḍakā samaṇakā ibbhā kaṇhā bandhupādāpaccā, "
"tehipi me saddhiṃ evaṃ kathāsallāpo hoti, yathariva bhotā gotamenā”ti. <a "
"class=\"wp\" id=\"wp1.11\"></a>“"
msgstr ""
"But as to these baldies, fake ascetics, riffraff, black spawn from the feet "
"of our Kinsman, I converse with them as I do with Master Gotama.”"

#. VAR: āgaccheyyātha → āgaccheyyātho (bj, pts1)
#. VAR: manasi kareyyātha → manasi kareyyātho (bj, pts1)
msgctxt "dn3:16.4"
msgid ""
"Atthikavato kho pana te, ambaṭṭha, idhāgamanaṃ ahosi, yāyeva kho panatthāya "
"āgaccheyyātha, tameva atthaṃ sādhukaṃ manasi kareyyātha."
msgstr ""
"“But Ambaṭṭha, you must have come here for some purpose. You should focus on "
"that."

msgctxt "dn3:16.5"
msgid ""
"Avusitavāyeva kho pana, bho, ayaṃ ambaṭṭho māṇavo vusitamānī kimaññatra "
"avusitattā”ti."
msgstr ""
"Though this Ambaṭṭha is unqualified, he thinks he’s qualified. What is that "
"but lack of qualifications?”"

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="12"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.12"></a><a
#. class="pts" id="pts1.91"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:17.1"
msgid ""
"Atha kho ambaṭṭho māṇavo bhagavatā avusitavādena vuccamāno kupito anattamano "
"bhagavantaṃyeva khuṃsento bhagavantaṃyeva vambhento bhagavantaṃyeva "
"upavadamāno:"
msgstr ""
"When he said this, Subha became angry and upset with the Buddha because of "
"being described as unqualified. He even attacked and badmouthed the Buddha "
"himself, saying:"

msgctxt "dn3:17.2"
msgid "“samaṇo ca me bho gotamo pāpito bhavissatī”ti bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:"
msgstr "“The ascetic Gotama will be worsted!” He said to the Buddha:"

msgctxt "dn3:17.3"
msgid "“caṇḍā, bho gotama, sakyajāti;"
msgstr "“Master Gotama, the Sakyan clan are rude,"

msgctxt "dn3:17.4"
msgid "pharusā, bho gotama, sakyajāti;"
msgstr "harsh,"

msgctxt "dn3:17.5"
msgid "lahusā, bho gotama, sakyajāti;"
msgstr "touchy,"

# Both RD and Walshe have "violent" evidently reading rabhasa. But that word is, so far as I know, unattested elsewhere. Note that pharusa is almost always used in the context of speech, and that lahusa seems to make more sense in talking of people who are "touchy", hard to talk to, rather than physically violent. Hence I prefer the reading bhassa, which is obviously the reading of the comm: Bhassāti bahubhāṇino. moreover, the story below hardly justifies the epithet "violent".
msgctxt "dn3:17.6"
msgid "bhassā, bho gotama, sakyajāti;"
msgstr "and argumentative."

#. VAR: garuṃ karonti → garukaronti (bj, s1-3, km, pts1)
msgctxt "dn3:17.7"
msgid ""
"ibbhā santā ibbhā samānā na brāhmaṇe sakkaronti, na brāhmaṇe garuṃ karonti, "
"na brāhmaṇe mānenti, na brāhmaṇe pūjenti, na brāhmaṇe apacāyanti."
msgstr ""
"Riffraff they are, and riffraff they remain! They don’t honor, respect, "
"revere, worship, or venerate brahmins."

msgctxt "dn3:17.8"
msgid ""
"Tayidaṃ, bho gotama, nacchannaṃ, tayidaṃ nappatirūpaṃ, yadime sakyā ibbhā "
"santā ibbhā samānā na brāhmaṇe sakkaronti, na brāhmaṇe garuṃ karonti, na "
"brāhmaṇe mānenti, na brāhmaṇe pūjenti, na brāhmaṇe apacāyantī”ti."
msgstr ""
"It is neither proper nor appropriate that the Sakyans—riffraff that they "
"are—don’t honor, respect, revere, worship, or venerate brahmins.”"

msgctxt "dn3:17.9"
msgid "Itiha ambaṭṭho māṇavo idaṃ paṭhamaṃ sakyesu ibbhavādaṃ nipātesi."
msgstr ""
"And that’s how Ambaṭṭha denigrated the Sakyans with the word “riffraff” for "
"the first time."

#. </p><h3>
msgctxt "dn3:18.1"
msgid "2.2. Dutiyaibbhavāda"
msgstr "The Second Use of the Word “Riffraff”"

#. </h3><p><a class="sc" id="13"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.13"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:19.1"
msgid "“Kiṃ pana te, ambaṭṭha, sakyā aparaddhun”ti?"
msgstr "“But Ambaṭṭha, how have the Sakyans wronged you?”"

msgctxt "dn3:19.2"
msgid ""
"“Ekamidāhaṃ, bho gotama, samayaṃ ācariyassa brāhmaṇassa pokkharasātissa "
"kenacideva karaṇīyena kapilavatthuṃ agamāsiṃ."
msgstr ""
"“This one time, Master Gotama, my teacher, the brahmin Pokkharasāti, went to "
"Kapilavatthu on some business."

msgctxt "dn3:19.3"
msgid "Yena sakyānaṃ sandhāgāraṃ tenupasaṅkamiṃ."
msgstr "He approached the Sakyans in their meeting hall."

#. VAR: sandhāgāre → santhāgāre (bj, pts1)
msgctxt "dn3:19.4"
msgid ""
"Tena kho pana samayena sambahulā sakyā ceva sakyakumārā ca sandhāgāre uccesu "
"āsanesu nisinnā honti aññamaññaṃ aṅgulipatodakehi sañjagghantā saṅkīḷantā, "
"aññadatthu mamaññeva maññe anujagghantā, na maṃ koci āsanenapi nimantesi."
msgstr ""
"Now at that time several Sakyans and Sakyan princes were sitting on high "
"seats, poking each other with their fingers, giggling and playing together. "
"In fact, they even presumed to giggle at me, and didn’t invite me to a seat."

msgctxt "dn3:19.5"
msgid ""
"Tayidaṃ, bho gotama, nacchannaṃ, tayidaṃ nappatirūpaṃ, yadime sakyā ibbhā "
"santā ibbhā samānā na brāhmaṇe sakkaronti, na brāhmaṇe garuṃ karonti, na "
"brāhmaṇe mānenti, na brāhmaṇe pūjenti, na brāhmaṇe apacāyantī”ti."
msgstr ""
"It is neither proper nor appropriate that the Sakyans—riffraff that they "
"are—don’t honor, respect, revere, worship, or venerate brahmins.”"

msgctxt "dn3:19.6"
msgid "Itiha ambaṭṭho māṇavo idaṃ dutiyaṃ sakyesu ibbhavādaṃ nipātesi."
msgstr ""
"And that’s how Ambaṭṭha denigrated the Sakyans with the word “riffraff” for "
"the second time."

#. </p><h3>
msgctxt "dn3:20.1"
msgid "2.3. Tatiyaibbhavāda"
msgstr "The Third Use of the Word “Riffraff”"

#. </h3><p><a class="sc" id="14"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.14"></a><a
#. class="pts" id="pts1.92"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:21.1"
msgid "“Laṭukikāpi kho, ambaṭṭha, sakuṇikā sake kulāvake kāmalāpinī hoti."
msgstr "“Even a little quail, Ambaṭṭha, speaks as she likes in her own nest."

# The Buddha's use of ayasma, ignored by both RD and W, is noteworthy here: the Buddha is taking a conciliatory tone.
msgctxt "dn3:21.2"
msgid ""
"Sakaṃ kho panetaṃ, ambaṭṭha, sakyānaṃ yadidaṃ kapilavatthuṃ, nārahatāyasmā "
"ambaṭṭho imāya appamattāya abhisajjitun”ti."
msgstr ""
"Kapilavatthu is the Sakyans own place, Ambaṭṭha. It’s not worthy of the "
"Venerable Ambaṭṭha to lose his temper over such a small thing.”"

msgctxt "dn3:21.3"
msgid "“Cattārome, bho gotama, vaṇṇā—"
msgstr "“Master Gotama, there are these four castes:"

msgctxt "dn3:21.4"
msgid "khattiyā brāhmaṇā vessā suddā."
msgstr "aristocrats, brahmins, merchants, and workers."

msgctxt "dn3:21.5"
msgid "Imesañhi, bho gotama, catunnaṃ vaṇṇānaṃ tayo vaṇṇā—"
msgstr "Three of these castes—"

msgctxt "dn3:21.6"
msgid "khattiyā ca vessā ca suddā ca—"
msgstr "aristocrats, merchants, and workers—"

msgctxt "dn3:21.7"
msgid "aññadatthu brāhmaṇasseva paricārakā sampajjanti."
msgstr "in fact succeed only in serving the brahmins."

msgctxt "dn3:21.8"
msgid ""
"Tayidaṃ, bho gotama, nacchannaṃ, tayidaṃ nappatirūpaṃ, yadime sakyā ibbhā "
"santā ibbhā samānā na brāhmaṇe sakkaronti, na brāhmaṇe garuṃ karonti, na "
"brāhmaṇe mānenti, na brāhmaṇe pūjenti, na brāhmaṇe apacāyantī”ti."
msgstr ""
"It is neither proper nor appropriate that the Sakyans—riffraff that they "
"are—don’t honor, respect, revere, worship, or venerate brahmins.”"

msgctxt "dn3:21.9"
msgid "Itiha ambaṭṭho māṇavo idaṃ tatiyaṃ sakyesu ibbhavādaṃ nipātesi."
msgstr ""
"And that’s how Ambaṭṭha denigrated the Sakyans with the word “riffraff” for "
"the third time."

#. </p><h3>
msgctxt "dn3:22.1"
msgid "2.4. Dāsiputtavāda"
msgstr "The Word “Son of Bondservants” is Used"

#. </h3><p><a class="sc" id="15"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.15"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:23.1"
msgid "Atha kho bhagavato etadahosi:"
msgstr "Then it occurred to the Buddha:"

msgctxt "dn3:23.2"
msgid ""
"“atibāḷhaṃ kho ayaṃ ambaṭṭho māṇavo sakyesu ibbhavādena nimmādeti, "
"yannūnāhaṃ gottaṃ puccheyyan”ti."
msgstr ""
"“This Ambaṭṭha puts the Sakyans down too much by calling them riffraff. Why "
"don’t I ask him about his own clan?”"

msgctxt "dn3:23.3"
msgid "Atha kho bhagavā ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ etadavoca:"
msgstr "So the Buddha said to him:"

msgctxt "dn3:23.4"
msgid "“kathaṃ gottosi, ambaṭṭhā”ti?"
msgstr "“What is your clan, Ambaṭṭha?”"

msgctxt "dn3:23.5"
msgid "“Kaṇhāyanohamasmi, bho gotamā”ti."
msgstr "“I am a Kaṇhāyana, Master Gotama.”"

# Normally I take ayyaputta as a simple honorific, but here Comm says Ayyaputtāti sāmino puttā. Dāsiputtoti gharadāsiyāva putto. Given the parallelism between these two phrases, and the fact that just below they are said to claim descent from Okkaka, it seems that the sense is not that the sakyansa were the masters, but were descended from them. Not much of a difference, I know!
msgctxt "dn3:23.6"
msgid ""
"“Porāṇaṃ kho pana te, ambaṭṭha, mātāpettikaṃ nāmagottaṃ anussarato ayyaputtā "
"sakyā bhavanti;"
msgstr ""
"“But, recollecting the ancient name and clan of your mother and father, the "
"Sakyans were the children of the masters, while you’re descended from the "
"son of a female bondservant of the Sakyans."

#, fuzzy
msgctxt "dn3:23.7"
msgid "dāsiputto tvamasi sakyānaṃ."
msgstr " "

msgctxt "dn3:23.8"
msgid "Sakyā kho pana, ambaṭṭha, rājānaṃ okkākaṃ pitāmahaṃ dahanti."
msgstr "But the Sakyans claim King Okkāka as their grandfather."

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="16"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:24.1"
msgid ""
"Bhūtapubbaṃ, ambaṭṭha, rājā okkāko yā sā mahesī piyā manāpā, tassā puttassa "
"rajjaṃ pariṇāmetukāmo jeṭṭhakumāre raṭṭhasmā pabbājesi—"
msgstr ""
"Once upon a time, King Okkāka, wishing to divert the royal succession to the "
"son of his most beloved queen, banished the elder princes from the realm—"

#. VAR: karakaṇḍaṃ → karakaṇḍuṃ (s1-3) | karaṇḍuṃ (pts1)
#. VAR: sinisūraṃ → nipuraṃ (bj) | sinipuraṃ (s1-3) | sīnipuraṃ (pts1)
#. VAR: okkāmukhaṃ → ukkāmukhaṃ (bj, s1-3)
msgctxt "dn3:24.2"
msgid "okkāmukhaṃ karakaṇḍaṃ hatthinikaṃ sinisūraṃ."
msgstr "Okkāmukha, Karakaṇḍa, Hatthinika, and Sinisūra."

msgctxt "dn3:24.3"
msgid ""
"Te raṭṭhasmā pabbājitā himavantapasse pokkharaṇiyā tīre mahāsākasaṇḍo, "
"tattha vāsaṃ kappesuṃ."
msgstr ""
"They made their home beside a lotus pond on the slopes of the Himalayas, "
"where there was a large teak grove."

# For sambheda, see AN 2.9=DN 26, AN 5.103 = AN 10.45. In each case the sense is not "breaking, destroying" as you might expect, but the dissolving of boundaries, resulting in promiscuity or leaking of secrets. Comm. to DN 26 has "Sambhedanti missībhāvaṃ, mariyādabhedaṃ vā."
msgctxt "dn3:24.4"
msgid "Te jātisambhedabhayā sakāhi bhaginīhi saddhiṃ saṃvāsaṃ kappesuṃ."
msgstr "For fear of diluting their lineage, they slept with their own sisters."

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="17"></a><a class="pts" id="pts1.93"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:25.1"
msgid "Atha kho, ambaṭṭha, rājā okkāko amacce pārisajje āmantesi:"
msgstr "Then King Okkaka addressed his ministers and counselors:"

# For this sense of sammati, see SN 11.9, SN 11.10
msgctxt "dn3:25.2"
msgid "‘kahaṃ nu kho, bho, etarahi kumārā sammantī’ti?"
msgstr "‘Where, sirs, have the princes settled now?’"

msgctxt "dn3:25.3"
msgid ""
"‘Atthi, deva, himavantapasse pokkharaṇiyā tīre mahāsākasaṇḍo, tatthetarahi "
"kumārā sammanti."
msgstr ""
"‘Sire, there is a lotus pond on the slopes of the Himalayas, by a large "
"grove of <i>sāka</i>, the teak tree. They’ve settled there."

msgctxt "dn3:25.4"
msgid "Te jātisambhedabhayā sakāhi bhaginīhi saddhiṃ saṃvāsaṃ kappentī’ti."
msgstr ""
"For fear of diluting their lineage, they are sleeping with their own "
"(<i>saka</i>) sisters.’"

msgctxt "dn3:25.5"
msgid "Atha kho, ambaṭṭha, rājā okkāko udānaṃ udānesi:"
msgstr "Then King Ambaṭṭha spoke these words of inspiration:"

# Not, one might imagine, the kind of response one might expect from the revelation of incest in one's children. Both RD and MW comment on the puns in this passage, but don't, unless I am missing something, mention the incest. Most likely there was speculation about the derivation of sakya, with some suggesting it was from saka, others from sāka, and, in the inclusive way of myths, this little story attempts to reconcile them. That it includes a memory of incestuous relations among the royal families is by no means unusual in such stories.
msgctxt "dn3:25.6"
msgid "‘sakyā vata, bho, kumārā, paramasakyā vata, bho, kumārā’ti."
msgstr ""
"‘The princes are indeed Sakyans! The princes are indeed the best Sakyans!’"

msgctxt "dn3:25.7"
msgid "Tadagge kho pana, ambaṭṭha, sakyā paññāyanti;"
msgstr "From that day on the Sakyans were recognized, and he was their founder."

#, fuzzy
msgctxt "dn3:25.8"
msgid "so ca nesaṃ pubbapuriso."
msgstr " "

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="18"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.16"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:26.1"
msgid "Rañño kho pana, ambaṭṭha, okkākassa disā nāma dāsī ahosi."
msgstr "Now, King Okkāka had a female bondservant named Disā."

# I'm very conflicted as to whether to include nama here! The whole passage seems to hover between treating kanha as a personal name, a description, or as a word for "demon". I try to capture this ambiguity by using variations of black boy. 
#. VAR: kaṇhaṃ nāma → sā kaṇhaṃ (pts1)
msgctxt "dn3:26.2"
msgid "Sā kaṇhaṃ nāma janesi."
msgstr "She gave birth to a black boy."

msgctxt "dn3:26.3"
msgid "Jāto kaṇho pabyāhāsi:"
msgstr "When he was born, Black Boy said:"

# His words here are clearly meant as a dramatic contrast with Siddhattha's birth.
msgctxt "dn3:26.4"
msgid ""
"‘dhovatha maṃ, amma, nahāpetha maṃ amma, imasmā maṃ asucismā parimocetha, "
"atthāya vo bhavissāmī’ti."
msgstr ""
"‘Wash me, mum, bathe me! Get this filth off of me! I will be useful for you!’"

msgctxt "dn3:26.5"
msgid ""
"Yathā kho pana, ambaṭṭha, etarahi manussā pisāce disvā ‘pisācā’ti sañjānanti;"
msgstr "Whereas these days when people see goblins they know them as goblins,"

msgctxt "dn3:26.6"
msgid ""
"evameva kho, ambaṭṭha, tena kho pana samayena manussā pisāce ‘kaṇhā’ti "
"sañjānanti."
msgstr "in those days they knew goblins as ‘blackboys’."

msgctxt "dn3:26.7"
msgid "Te evamāhaṃsu:"
msgstr "They said:"

msgctxt "dn3:26.8"
msgid "‘ayaṃ jāto pabyāhāsi, kaṇho jāto, pisāco jāto’ti."
msgstr "‘He spoke as soon as he was born—a blackboy is born! A goblin is born!’"

msgctxt "dn3:26.9"
msgid ""
"Tadagge kho pana, ambaṭṭha, kaṇhāyanā paññāyanti, so ca kaṇhāyanānaṃ "
"pubbapuriso."
msgstr ""
"From that day on the Kaṇhāyanas were recognized, and he was their founder."

msgctxt "dn3:26.10"
msgid ""
"Iti kho te, ambaṭṭha, porāṇaṃ mātāpettikaṃ nāmagottaṃ anussarato ayyaputtā "
"sakyā bhavanti, dāsiputto tvamasi sakyānan”ti."
msgstr ""
"That’s how, recollecting the ancient name and clan of your mother and "
"father, the Sakyans were the children of the masters, while you’re descended "
"from the son of a female bondservant of the Sakyans.”"

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="19"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.17"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:27.1"
msgid "Evaṃ vutte, te māṇavakā bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:"
msgstr "When he said this, those students said to him:"

msgctxt "dn3:27.2"
msgid "“mā bhavaṃ gotamo ambaṭṭhaṃ atibāḷhaṃ dāsiputtavādena nimmādesi."
msgstr ""
"“Master Gotama, please don’t put Ambaṭṭha down too much by calling him the "
"son of a bondservant."

msgctxt "dn3:27.3"
msgid ""
"Sujāto ca, bho gotama, ambaṭṭho māṇavo, kulaputto ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, "
"bahussuto ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, kalyāṇavākkaraṇo ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, paṇḍito "
"ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, pahoti ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo bhotā gotamena saddhiṃ asmiṃ "
"vacane paṭimantetun”ti."
msgstr ""
"He’s well-born, respectable, learned, a good speaker, and astute. He’s "
"capable of having a dialogue with Master Gotama about this.” "

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="20"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.18"></a><a
#. class="pts" id="pts1.94"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:28.1"
msgid "Atha kho bhagavā te māṇavake etadavoca:"
msgstr "So the Buddha said to them:"

msgctxt "dn3:28.2"
msgid "“sace kho tumhākaṃ māṇavakānaṃ evaṃ hoti:"
msgstr "“Well, students, if you think that"

#. VAR: mantavho → mantayavho (bj)
msgctxt "dn3:28.3"
msgid ""
"‘dujjāto ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, akulaputto ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, appassuto ca "
"ambaṭṭho māṇavo, akalyāṇavākkaraṇo ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, duppañño ca ambaṭṭho "
"māṇavo, na ca pahoti ambaṭṭho māṇavo samaṇena gotamena saddhiṃ asmiṃ vacane "
"paṭimantetun’ti, tiṭṭhatu ambaṭṭho māṇavo, tumhe mayā saddhiṃ mantavho asmiṃ "
"vacane."
msgstr ""
"Ambaṭṭha is ill-born, not respectable, uneducated, a poor speaker, witless, "
"and not capable of having a dialogue with me about this, then leave him "
"aside and you can have a dialogue with me."

msgctxt "dn3:28.4"
msgid "Sace pana tumhākaṃ māṇavakānaṃ evaṃ hoti:"
msgstr "But if you think that"

msgctxt "dn3:28.5"
msgid ""
"‘sujāto ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, kulaputto ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, bahussuto ca "
"ambaṭṭho māṇavo, kalyāṇavākkaraṇo ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, paṇḍito ca ambaṭṭho "
"māṇavo, pahoti ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo samaṇena gotamena saddhiṃ asmiṃ vacane "
"paṭimantetun’ti, tiṭṭhatha tumhe;"
msgstr ""
"he’s well-born, respectable, learned, a good speaker, astute, and capable of "
"having a dialogue with me about this, then you should stand aside and let "
"him have a dialogue with me.”"

msgctxt "dn3:28.6"
msgid "ambaṭṭho māṇavo mayā saddhiṃ paṭimantetū”ti."
msgstr " "

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="21"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.19"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:29.1"
msgid ""
"“Sujāto ca, bho gotama, ambaṭṭho māṇavo, kulaputto ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, "
"bahussuto ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, kalyāṇavākkaraṇo ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, paṇḍito "
"ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, pahoti ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo bhotā gotamena saddhiṃ asmiṃ "
"vacane paṭimantetuṃ, tuṇhī mayaṃ bhavissāma, ambaṭṭho māṇavo bhotā gotamena "
"saddhiṃ asmiṃ vacane paṭimantetū”ti."
msgstr ""
"“He is capable of having a dialogue. We will be silent, and let Ambaṭṭha "
"have a dialogue with Master Gotama.”"

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="22"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.20"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:30.1"
msgid "Atha kho bhagavā ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ etadavoca:"
msgstr "So the Buddha said to Ambaṭṭha:"

msgctxt "dn3:30.2"
msgid ""
"“ayaṃ kho pana te, ambaṭṭha, sahadhammiko pañho āgacchati, akāmā byākātabbo."
msgstr ""
"“Well, Ambaṭṭha, there’s a legitimate question that comes up. You won’t like "
"it, but you ought to answer anyway."

# Both RD and MW misconstrue the syntax here. There are three vā-s, i.e. three ways of not answering.
msgctxt "dn3:30.3"
msgid ""
"Sace tvaṃ na byākarissasi, aññena vā aññaṃ paṭicarissasi, tuṇhī vā "
"bhavissasi, pakkamissasi vā ettheva te sattadhā muddhā phalissati."
msgstr ""
"If you don’t answer, but dodge the issue, remain silent, or simply leave, "
"your head will explode into seven pieces right here."

msgctxt "dn3:30.4"
msgid ""
"Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ambaṭṭha, kinti te sutaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ vuddhānaṃ mahallakānaṃ "
"ācariyapācariyānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ kutopabhutikā kaṇhāyanā, ko ca kaṇhāyanānaṃ "
"pubbapuriso”ti?"
msgstr ""
"What do you think, Ambaṭṭha? According to what you have you heard from "
"elderly and senior brahmins, the teachers of teachers, what is the origin of "
"the Kaṇhāyanas, and who is their founder?”"

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="23"></a><a class="pts" id="pts1.95"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:31.1"
msgid "Evaṃ vutte, ambaṭṭho māṇavo tuṇhī ahosi."
msgstr "When he said this, Ambaṭṭha kept silent."

msgctxt "dn3:31.2"
msgid "Dutiyampi kho bhagavā ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ etadavoca:"
msgstr "For a second time, the Buddha put the question,"

msgctxt "dn3:31.3"
msgid ""
"“taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ambaṭṭha, kinti te sutaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ vuddhānaṃ "
"mahallakānaṃ ācariyapācariyānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ kutopabhutikā kaṇhāyanā, ko ca "
"kaṇhāyanānaṃ pubbapuriso”ti?"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "dn3:31.4"
msgid "Dutiyampi kho ambaṭṭho māṇavo tuṇhī ahosi."
msgstr "and for a second time Ambaṭṭha kept silent."

msgctxt "dn3:31.5"
msgid "Atha kho bhagavā ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ etadavoca:"
msgstr "So the Buddha said to him:"

msgctxt "dn3:31.6"
msgid "“byākarohi dāni, ambaṭṭha, na dāni, te tuṇhībhāvassa kālo."
msgstr "“Answer now, Ambaṭṭha. Now is not the time for silence."

msgctxt "dn3:31.7"
msgid ""
"Yo kho, ambaṭṭha, tathāgatena yāvatatiyakaṃ sahadhammikaṃ pañhaṃ puṭṭho na "
"byākaroti, etthevassa sattadhā muddhā phalissatī”ti."
msgstr ""
"If someone fails to answer a legitimate question when asked three times by "
"the Buddha, their head explodes into seven pieces there and then.”"

# Cp. MN 35
#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="24"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.21"></a>
#. VAR: sajotibhūtaṃ → saṃjotibhūtaṃ (s1-3)
msgctxt "dn3:32.1"
msgid ""
"Tena kho pana samayena vajirapāṇī yakkho mahantaṃ ayokūṭaṃ ādāya ādittaṃ "
"sampajjalitaṃ sajotibhūtaṃ ambaṭṭhassa māṇavassa upari vehāsaṃ ṭhito hoti:"
msgstr ""
"Now at that time the spirit Vajirapāṇi, holding a massive iron spear, "
"burning, blazing, and glowing, stood in the sky above Ambaṭṭha, thinking:"

msgctxt "dn3:32.2"
msgid ""
"“sacāyaṃ ambaṭṭho māṇavo bhagavatā yāvatatiyakaṃ sahadhammikaṃ pañhaṃ puṭṭho "
"na byākarissati, etthevassa sattadhā muddhaṃ phālessāmī”ti."
msgstr ""
"“If this Ambaṭṭha doesn’t answer when asked a third time, I’ll blow his head "
"into seven pieces there and then!”"

msgctxt "dn3:32.3"
msgid ""
"Taṃ kho pana vajirapāṇiṃ yakkhaṃ bhagavā ceva passati ambaṭṭho ca māṇavo."
msgstr "And both the Buddha and Ambaṭṭha could see Vajirapāṇi."

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="25"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:33.1"
msgid ""
"Atha kho ambaṭṭho māṇavo bhīto saṃviggo lomahaṭṭhajāto bhagavantaṃyeva tāṇaṃ "
"gavesī bhagavantaṃyeva leṇaṃ gavesī bhagavantaṃyeva saraṇaṃ gavesī "
"upanisīditvā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:"
msgstr ""
"Ambaṭṭha was terrified, shocked, and awestruck. Looking to the Buddha for "
"shelter, protection, and refuge, he sat down close by the Buddha and said:"

#. VAR: kimetaṃ → kiṃ me taṃ (bj, mr)
msgctxt "dn3:33.2"
msgid "“kimetaṃ bhavaṃ gotamo āha?"
msgstr "“What did you say?"

#. VAR: bravitū”ti → brūtūti (s1-3) | brūmetūti (pts1)
msgctxt "dn3:33.3"
msgid "Punabhavaṃ gotamo bravitū”ti."
msgstr "Please repeat the question.”"

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="26"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:34.1"
msgid ""
"“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ambaṭṭha, kinti te sutaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ vuddhānaṃ "
"mahallakānaṃ ācariyapācariyānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ kutopabhutikā kaṇhāyanā, ko ca "
"kaṇhāyanānaṃ pubbapuriso”ti?"
msgstr ""
"“What do you think, Ambaṭṭha? According to what you have you heard from "
"elderly and senior brahmins, the teachers of teachers, what is the origin of "
"the Kaṇhāyanas, and who is their founder?”"

msgctxt "dn3:34.2"
msgid "“Evameva me, bho gotama, sutaṃ yatheva bhavaṃ gotamo āha."
msgstr "“I have heard, Master Gotama, that it is just as you say."

msgctxt "dn3:34.3"
msgid "Tatopabhutikā kaṇhāyanā;"
msgstr "That’s the origin of the Kaṇhāyanas,"

msgctxt "dn3:34.4"
msgid "so ca kaṇhāyanānaṃ pubbapuriso”ti."
msgstr "and that’s who their founder is.”"

#. </p><h3>
msgctxt "dn3:35.1"
msgid "2.5. Ambaṭṭhavaṃsakathā"
msgstr "The Discussion of Ambaṭṭha’s Heritage"

#. </h3><p><a class="sc" id="27"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.22"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:36.1"
msgid "Evaṃ vutte, te māṇavakā unnādino uccāsaddamahāsaddā ahesuṃ:"
msgstr "When he said this, those students made an uproar:"

msgctxt "dn3:36.2"
msgid "“dujjāto kira, bho, ambaṭṭho māṇavo;"
msgstr ""
"“It turns out Ambaṭṭha is ill-born, not respectable, son of a Sakyan "
"bondservant, and that the Sakyans are sons of his masters!"

#, fuzzy
msgctxt "dn3:36.3"
msgid "akulaputto kira, bho, ambaṭṭho māṇavo;"
msgstr " "

msgctxt "dn3:36.4"
msgid "dāsiputto kira, bho, ambaṭṭho māṇavo sakyānaṃ."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "dn3:36.5"
msgid "Ayyaputtā kira, bho, ambaṭṭhassa māṇavassa sakyā bhavanti."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "dn3:36.6"
msgid "Dhammavādiṃyeva kira mayaṃ samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ apasādetabbaṃ amaññimhā”ti."
msgstr ""
"And it seems that the ascetic Gotama spoke only the truth, though we "
"presumed to rebuke him!”"

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="28"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.23"></a><a
#. class="pts" id="pts1.96"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:37.1"
msgid "Atha kho bhagavato etadahosi:"
msgstr "Then it occurred to the Buddha:"

msgctxt "dn3:37.2"
msgid ""
"“atibāḷhaṃ kho ime māṇavakā ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ dāsiputtavādena nimmādenti, "
"yannūnāhaṃ parimoceyyan”ti."
msgstr ""
"“These students puts Ambaṭṭha down too much by calling him the son of a "
"bondservant. Why don’t I get him out of this?”"

msgctxt "dn3:37.3"
msgid "Atha kho bhagavā te māṇavake etadavoca:"
msgstr "So the Buddha said to the students:"

msgctxt "dn3:37.4"
msgid ""
"“mā kho tumhe, māṇavakā, ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ atibāḷhaṃ dāsiputtavādena "
"nimmādetha."
msgstr ""
"“Students, please don’t put Ambaṭṭha down too much by calling him the son of "
"a bondservant."

msgctxt "dn3:37.5"
msgid "Uḷāro so kaṇho isi ahosi."
msgstr "That Black Boy was an eminent sage."

# Brahmamanta is of unique occurence, and neither RD's "mystic verses" nor MW's "mantras of the Brahmins" is adequate. the former is too vague, the second—while hardly being a translation at all—manages to get the basics wrong, as it is brahma, not brahmana. Comm says: brahmamanteti ānubhāvasampannatāya seṭṭhamante. And, while the connection to brahmanism is too obvious to need mentioning, i think it is right in saying this is a specially powerful spell.
msgctxt "dn3:37.6"
msgid ""
"So dakkhiṇajanapadaṃ gantvā brahmamante adhīyitvā rājānaṃ okkākaṃ "
"upasaṅkamitvā maddarūpiṃ dhītaraṃ yāci."
msgstr ""
"He went to a southern country and memorized the Prime Spell. Then he "
"approached King Okkāka and asked for the hand of his daughter Maddarūpī."

msgctxt "dn3:37.7"
msgid "Tassa rājā okkāko:"
msgstr "The king said to him:"

#. VAR: sannayhi → sannahi (mr)
msgctxt "dn3:37.8"
msgid ""
"‘ko nevaṃ re ayaṃ mayhaṃ dāsiputto samāno maddarūpiṃ dhītaraṃ yācatī’ti, "
"kupito anattamano khurappaṃ sannayhi."
msgstr ""
"‘Who the hell is this son of a bondservant to ask for the hand of my "
"daughter!’ Angry and upset he fastened a razor-tipped arrow."

msgctxt "dn3:37.9"
msgid "So taṃ khurappaṃ neva asakkhi muñcituṃ, no paṭisaṃharituṃ."
msgstr "But he wasn’t able to either shoot it or to relax it."

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="29"></a><a class="pts" id="pts1.97"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:38.1"
msgid ""
"Atha kho, māṇavakā, amaccā pārisajjā kaṇhaṃ isiṃ upasaṅkamitvā etadavocuṃ:"
msgstr ""
"Then the ministers and counselors approached the sage Black Boy and said:"

#. VAR: bhaddante → bhadante (bj, s1-3, pts1)
msgctxt "dn3:38.2"
msgid "‘sotthi, bhaddante, hotu rañño;"
msgstr "‘Spare the king, sir,"

msgctxt "dn3:38.3"
msgid "sotthi, bhaddante, hotu rañño’ti."
msgstr "spare him!’"

msgctxt "dn3:38.4"
msgid ""
"‘Sotthi bhavissati rañño, api ca rājā yadi adho khurappaṃ muñcissati, yāvatā "
"rañño vijitaṃ, ettāvatā pathavī undriyissatī’ti."
msgstr ""
"‘The king will be safe. But if he shoots the arrow downwards, there will be "
"an earthquake across the entire realm.’"

msgctxt "dn3:38.5"
msgid "‘Sotthi, bhaddante, hotu rañño, sotthi janapadassā’ti."
msgstr "‘Spare the king, sir, and spare the country!’"

msgctxt "dn3:38.6"
msgid ""
"‘Sotthi bhavissati rañño, sotthi janapadassa, api ca rājā yadi uddhaṃ "
"khurappaṃ muñcissati, yāvatā rañño vijitaṃ, ettāvatā satta vassāni devo na "
"vassissatī’ti."
msgstr ""
"‘Both king and country will be safe. But if he shoots the arrow upwards, "
"there will be no rain in the entire realm for seven years.’"

# This is obviously an origin story for this prayer.
msgctxt "dn3:38.7"
msgid "‘Sotthi, bhaddante, hotu rañño sotthi janapadassa devo ca vassatū’ti."
msgstr "‘Spare the king, sir, spare the country, and let there be rain!’"

# National prosperity through fake regicide. How did Frazer miss this?
msgctxt "dn3:38.8"
msgid ""
"‘Sotthi bhavissati rañño sotthi janapadassa devo ca vassissati, api ca rājā "
"jeṭṭhakumāre khurappaṃ patiṭṭhāpetu, sotthi kumāro pallomo bhavissatī’ti."
msgstr ""
"‘Both king and country will be safe, and the rain will fall. And if the king "
"aims the arrow at the crown prince, he will be safe and untouched.’"

# The use of the bare personal name for the king is highly unusual, and not capture by either RD or MW.
msgctxt "dn3:38.9"
msgid "Atha kho, māṇavakā, amaccā okkākassa ārocesuṃ:"
msgstr "So the ministers said to Okkāka:"

msgctxt "dn3:38.10"
msgid "‘okkāko jeṭṭhakumāre khurappaṃ patiṭṭhāpetu."
msgstr ""
"‘Okkāka must aim the arrow at the crown prince. He will be safe and "
"untouched.’"

#, fuzzy
msgctxt "dn3:38.11"
msgid "Sotthi kumāro pallomo bhavissatī’ti."
msgstr " "

msgctxt "dn3:38.12"
msgid ""
"Atha kho rājā okkāko jeṭṭhakumāre khurappaṃ patiṭṭhapesi, sotthi kumāro "
"pallomo samabhavi."
msgstr ""
"So King Okkāka aimed the arrow at the crown prince. And he was safe and "
"untouched."

# Again, neither RD nor MW capture brahmadanda here: it clearly harks back to brahmamantra.
msgctxt "dn3:38.13"
msgid ""
"Atha kho tassa rājā okkāko bhīto saṃviggo lomahaṭṭhajāto brahmadaṇḍena "
"tajjito maddarūpiṃ dhītaraṃ adāsi."
msgstr ""
"Then the king was terrified, shocked, and awestruck. Scared by the prime "
"punishment, he gave the hand of his daughter Maddarūpī."

# So threatening the king and forcing an unwanted marriage is a sign of eminence?
msgctxt "dn3:38.14"
msgid ""
"Mā kho tumhe, māṇavakā, ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ atibāḷhaṃ dāsiputtavādena "
"nimmādetha, uḷāro so kaṇho isi ahosī”ti."
msgstr ""
"Students, please don’t put Ambaṭṭha down too much by calling him the son of "
"a bondservant. That Black Boy was an eminent sage.”"

#. </p><h2>
msgctxt "dn3:39.1"
msgid "3. Khattiyaseṭṭhabhāva"
msgstr "The Supremacy of the Aristocrats"

#. </h2><p><a class="sc" id="30"></a><a class="wp" id="wp1.24"></a>
msgctxt "dn3:40.1"
msgid "Atha kho bhagavā ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ āmantesi:"
msgstr "Then the Buddha addressed Ambaṭṭha:"

msgctxt "dn3:40.2"
msgid ""
"“taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ambaṭṭha, idha khattiyakumāro brāhmaṇakaññāya saddhiṃ "
"saṃvāsaṃ kappeyya, tesaṃ saṃvāsamanvāya putto jāyetha."
msgstr ""
"“What do you think, Ambaṭṭha? Suppose an aristocrat boy was to sleep with a "
"brahmin girl, and they had a son."

msgctxt "dn3:40.3"
msgid ""
"Yo so khattiyakumārena brāhmaṇakaññāya putto uppanno, api nu so labhetha "
"brāhmaṇesu āsanaṃ vā udakaṃ vā”ti?"
msgstr "Would he receive a seat and water from the brahmins?”"

msgctxt "dn3:40.4"
msgid "“Labhetha, bho gotama”."
msgstr "“He would, Master Gotama.”"

msgctxt "dn3:40.5"
msgid ""
"“Api nu naṃ brāhmaṇā bhojeyyuṃ saddhe vā thālipāke vā yaññe vā pāhune vā”ti?"
msgstr ""
"“And would the brahmins feed him at an offering of food for ancestors, an "
"offering of dish of milk-rice, a sacrifice, or a feast for guests?”"

msgctxt "dn3:40.6"
msgid "“Bhojeyyuṃ, bho gotama”."
msgstr "“They would.”"

msgctxt "dn3:40.7"
msgid "“Api nu naṃ brāhmaṇā mante vāceyyuṃ vā no vā”ti?"
msgstr "“And would the brahmins teach him the hymns or not?”"

msgctxt "dn3:40.8"
msgid "“Vāceyyuṃ, bho gotama”."
msgstr "“They would.”"

# Translation of avata here is tricky. I don't think it means "veiled", nor does it imply that the women are shut in, neither of which is, so far as I am aware, attested at this time. In MN 56 avata is used in reference to Upali "shutting his gate" against the Jains and opening it for the Buddhists. So here I think it basically means "excludes from close contact" (especially as a suitor). Cp DN 17, where it has a similar sense.
msgctxt "dn3:40.9"
msgid "“Api nussa itthīsu āvaṭaṃ vā assa anāvaṭaṃ vā”ti?"
msgstr "“And would he be kept from the women or not?”"

msgctxt "dn3:40.10"
msgid "“Anāvaṭaṃ hissa, bho gotama”."
msgstr "“He would not.”"

msgctxt "dn3:40.11"
msgid "“Api nu naṃ khattiyā khattiyābhisekena abhisiñceyyun”ti?"
msgstr "“And would the aristocrats anoint him as king?”"

msgctxt "dn3:40.12"
msgid "“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”."
msgstr "“No, Master Gotama."

msgctxt "dn3:40.13"
msgid "“Taṃ kissa hetu”?"
msgstr "Why is that? "

msgctxt "dn3:40.14"
msgid "“Mātito hi, bho gotama, anupapanno”ti."
msgstr "Because his maternity is unsuitable.”"

